<exercisegroup cols="2"><introduction><p>For Problems 55<ndash/>58, show that the equation is an identity by transforming the left side into the right side.</p></introduction>

    <exercise number="55"><statement><m>\dfrac{1 - \cos^2 \alpha}{\tan \alpha} = \sin \alpha \cos \alpha</m></statement>
    <answer><m>\dfrac{1 - \cos^2 \alpha}{\tan \alpha} = \sin^2 \alpha \cdot \dfrac{\cos \alpha}{\sin \alpha} = \sin \alpha \cos \alpha</m></answer></exercise>

    <exercise number="56"><statement><m>\cos^2 \beta \tan^2 \beta + \cos^2 \beta = 1</m></statement></exercise>

    <exercise number="57"><statement><m>\dfrac{\tan \theta - \sin \theta \cos \theta}{\sin \theta \cos \theta} = \sin \theta</m></statement>
    <answer>
        \begin{align*}
        \dfrac{\dfrac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta} - \sin \theta \cos \theta}{\sin \theta \cdot \dfrac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta}} \amp = \dfrac{\sin \theta - \sin \theta \cos^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \theta}\\ 
        \amp = \dfrac{\sin \theta (1 - \cos^2 \theta)}{\sin^2 \theta} = \dfrac{\sin \theta \sin^2 \theta}{\sin^2 \theta} = \sin \theta\\
        \end{align*}</answer></exercise>

    <exercise number="58"><statement><m>\tan \phi - \dfrac{\sin^2 \phi}{\tan \phi} = \tan \phi \sin^2 \phi</m></statement></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

